1 d. Effective responses to human trafficking situations, including how to report
2 suspected human trafficking to law enforcement.
3 3. A proprietor may:
4 a. Provide each onsite employee with the training described in subsection 2.
5 b. In an employee roster or in each employee's personnel file, annually certify each
6 employee has received the training approved by the human trafficking
7 commission.
8 c. Conduct an ongoing awareness campaign for employees which addresses the
9 information described in subsection 2.
10 4. A proprietor may post and maintain a poster approved and provided by the human
11 trafficking commission which contains the information described in subsection 2. The
12 poster must include the contact information for an organization that provides
13 assistance and support services to human trafficking victims. The poster may be
14 visibly displayed at the lodging establishment's check-in area, lobby, or transient guest
15 services.
16 5. An entity that regulates an occupation or profession may accept the training described
17 in subsection 2 for continuing education credit .
18 6. A proprietor or employee of a lodging establishment or a member of a regulated
19 occupation or profession who acts in good faith is immune from liability in any civil
20 action for reporting suspected human trafficking activities but a member of a regulated
21 occupation or profession may be subject to disciplinary action for the reporting if the
22 reporting violates an applicable ethics regulation imposed by the member's regulated
23 occupation or profession.
24 6.7. The human trafficking commission may seek, apply for, accept, and receive any
25 donation, gift, grant, or bequest offered or tendered from public or private sources for
26 the purpose of furthering the objectives of the human trafficking prevention training
27 and incentivizing proprietors and members of a regulated occupation or profession to
28 participate in the human trafficking prevention training. All moneys received or
29 accepted under this subsection are appropriated on a continuing basis to the human
30 trafficking commission.
